      {
        "id": 4011911,
        "name": "Jeff Leve",
        "username": "Jeff_Leve",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/ccd318/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2023-02-18T16:17:26.760Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-Grand_Cru_Cru\" data-username=\"NoahR\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"297599\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/noahr/48/2194_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> NoahR:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Opened for my birthday, along with a delicious 1977 Boak. A bit austere and tannic, keeping with the vintage, despite ample time in decanter. Decent density but not sweet. Tobacco and leafy in spades, a touch of saddle leather, cassis and tart berry fruit.</p>\n<p>This is a solid and rich Bordeaux, but it lacked finesse and never really blossomed into anything interesting, even after long decant. It has the density and tannins to age further. Whether it picks up a tertiary nuance that delights is a separate matter. I have one more bottle that I\u2019ll keep for another decade.</p>\n<p>I expect First Growths to blow me out of the water. This did not.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Happy BDay! But I might disagree a bit. 96 is a stellar vintage for Left Bank BDX. It\u2019s never been austere. The tannin structure has made many 96 Left Bank wines delicious since release.</p>\n<p>As for the Firsts and expectations, the Firsts can be above and beyond all the other wines, depending on the wine and the vintage. Both matter.</p>\n<p>Personally I really like 96 HB, it\u2019s a very good wine. FWIW, HB is always smoky and tobacco laden, but good bottles are never bretty. That seems like a faulty bottle, or you simply might not love HB. While very good, 96 is not a great HB, just very good. From 96, Latour, Lafite and Margaux are all much better wines.</p>\n<p>If you want a killer HB bottle, today, the best deal for a stunning HB with age is probably 98.</p>\n<p>Lastly, you don\u2019t need a First for a mind blowing experience, Pichon L, Pichon B, Montrose, Cos, Ducru, LLC, Palmer and others can offer as good or better tasting experiences for less.</p>",
