      {
        "id": 4012067,
        "name": "Jeff Leve",
        "username": "Jeff_Leve",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/ccd318/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2023-02-18T19:09:06.158Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-Grand_Cru_Cru\" data-username=\"NoahR\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"297599\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/noahr/48/2194_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> NoahR:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Jeff - you are right on all accounts - this was not a bretty bottle, but it was an auction bottle, so I cannot be assured of provenance. I expected more, given the year and the wine, and this was perhaps an off bottle. It wasn\u2019t tannic, it was tannic for 96. It wasn\u2019t austere, it was austere for my expectations of 96 HB. Your impression that it is a good-but-not-great HB is confirmed. I was just hoping for more\u2026</p>\n<p>I am in agreement that many other Bordeaux often match or surpass the first growths, which I why I rarely spring for them. My favorite Bordeaux in recent memory have been 86 Rauzan-Segla, 86 PLL, 89 Pichon Baron and 82 Gruaud Larose, all of which trade at 1/3 the price of any first growth from the same year. All of which were much more enjoyable than this bottle.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/images/emoji/unicode/slight_smile.png?v=12\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"> N</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Noah\u2026 2 final points. There is a moderate to high risk in buying single bottles at auction. Such is life and part of the game.</p>\n<p>In the FWIW category, I sold all my 86 Bordeaux but 3. The vintage is frankly too hard and austere for me. YMMV. The 89 PB and 82 GL are both First Growth in quality wines. 90 PB is at the same level, though all of those wines are no longer bargains. Until maybe 2 years ago, they were sitting around for about $200 for years.</p>\n<p>In the unsolicited advice section, find a friend or two, or a small group and share the cost of a top vintage of a First Growth as a group, it cuts down the cost and lets others share in the experience.</p>\n<p>I know you read my site. I taste these wines a lot, here, and in Bordeaux. Before buying a big money bottle, feel free to check it out first. We all have our own tastes, but you can determine the style of the wine in advance, which can make you a smarter buyer.</p>\n<p>IMO, a top vintage of HB is otherworldly as are many of the best wines.</p>",
